// parse_op.su — map an operator character to its op-code ON THE SUBSTRATE.
//
// op_code(s) reads the operator char at index 0 of the string s and returns the
// op-code switch.su expects: '+' -> 0, '-' -> 1, '*' -> 2, '/' -> 3. This removes
// the host-side CODE[op] dictionary from calc.py — which operation the
// calculator runs is now decided entirely on the substrate (op_code here selects
// the code; switch.su then selects the operation from the code).
//
// Mechanism (all substrate ops, same select+saturation pattern as switch.su):
//   - string_char_at(s, 0) gives the operator's codepoint as a real number
//     ('+' = 43, '-' = 45, '*' = 42, '/' = 47).
//   - score_op = -1000 * (cp - target)^2 is 0 at a match and <= -1000 otherwise,
//     so exp(score) underflows to exactly 0 off-match and select is a true
//     one-hot (no blend) — the matched op-code passes through.
//   - select returns the one-hot-chosen op-code vector; the host reads it with
//     real().
//
// Scope: the four arithmetic operators. A non-operator char gives the nearest
// op-code (no refusal here) — the caller (parse stage) is responsible for only
// passing an operator; a full substrate parser would gate this on "is this an
// operator char" upstream.
function vector op_code(string s) {
    scalar cp = s.string_char_at(0);
    scalar s_add = 0.0 - 1000.0 * (cp - 43.0) * (cp - 43.0);  // '+'
    scalar s_sub = 0.0 - 1000.0 * (cp - 45.0) * (cp - 45.0);  // '-'
    scalar s_mul = 0.0 - 1000.0 * (cp - 42.0) * (cp - 42.0);  // '*'
    scalar s_div = 0.0 - 1000.0 * (cp - 47.0) * (cp - 47.0);  // '/'
    return select(
        [s_add, s_sub, s_mul, s_div],
        [make_real(0.0), make_real(1.0), make_real(2.0), make_real(3.0)]
    );
}

function vector main() { return op_code("+"); }
